of people talking about the same thing. Everybody has already spoiled my talk. So if you learn

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:34.840
anything new, it probably isn't going to be about the R & Python playing nice part. Anyway.

00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:42.400
So in the next 15 to 18 minutes, I hope, I will give you guys an introduction and a project

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:49.959
overview. I will talk about how life tends to interfere with even the best plans and

00:00:49.959 --> 00:00:56.560
what strategies we use to get over those challenges that life threw at us in the middle

00:00:56.560 --> 00:00:59.840
of our project.

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:09.040
So I work for Continental Tire, or Conti as we like to call it. It is a big company. It's

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:17.559
been around for about 150 years, builds all kinds of different tires, and I have a soft

00:01:17.639 --> 00:01:24.080
spot for Conti, specifically because of that third tire in row there, because those are

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:31.239
the bicycle tires and I am a cyclist, as you can see here in this family photo of me with

00:01:31.239 --> 00:01:38.239
two of my favorite bikes. But no, we can't talk about bikes all day. We have to talk

00:01:38.239 --> 00:01:40.040
about tires.

00:01:40.919 --> 00:01:49.720
So tires are surprisingly complex. An average passenger car tire can have up to 200 components,

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:57.559
and those are built to certain specifications. If you look over here, aside from the rim

00:01:57.559 --> 00:02:07.239
size and such, we have the load index and the speed symbol for that tire. These specifications

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:13.039
we actually have to test for to make sure that our tires are performing as we expect

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:14.800
them to be.

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:23.520
So in Conti, we have been testing tires, well, obviously making tires for 150 years, right?

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:28.199
We've been testing for a long time, too. We have a lot of data on previous tire builds

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:36.880
and tests, and we wanted to combine the knowledge that we already have of tire testing and tire

00:02:36.919 --> 00:02:45.600
build to be able to predict the performance of tires before they are actually made.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:57.320
So we worked on this POC for about 18 months when it was approved for industrialization,

00:02:57.320 --> 00:03:05.460
and at about that same time, my project lead and peer, our developer, was also getting

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:13.300
ready to deliver something. Her human baby. And because this is a German company, I don't

00:03:13.300 --> 00:03:21.460
know if I skipped that part, but anyways, she took parental leave for two years. Yeah,

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:22.460
I know.

00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:32.979
So yes, some parts of the world actually put life first. Anyway, at that point, the team

00:03:32.979 --> 00:03:38.660
changed, and we had a language flip in the developers. We went from a three-quarters

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:46.779
R to Python to a, you know, Python to R, mostly Python developers.

00:03:46.779 --> 00:04:00.820
So this sort of threw me back into my childhood, I guess, and reminded me, oh, no, no, no,

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:11.059
I've got to set up a little more of my chip on my shoulder here.

00:04:11.059 --> 00:04:18.859
We must rewrite this all in Python. This was heard in some of those early meetings with

00:04:18.859 --> 00:04:25.260
that new team. Actually, somebody who was not going to contribute any developer time

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:35.339
was the one who said this. But at this point, and here I will digress with Blake, we had

00:04:35.339 --> 00:04:41.660
already put about 1,000 commits into the repository. We had the machine learning model already

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:49.220
deployed to our platform, and the only developer really available to do that would have been

00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:52.940
me. So it was a non-starter.

00:04:52.940 --> 00:05:03.380
And now I get thrown back into my young years, and I remember when Indiana Jones is looking

00:05:03.380 --> 00:05:13.420
over into the Well of Souls, and he sees the entire ground just completely covered in snakes.

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:23.940
Why did it have to be snakes? And if nobody got that analogy, yes, snakes, Python, right?

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:31.140
So to be able to move forward here and actually get this going, which was going to be the

00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:40.420
first machine learning model, you know, productive, sorry, not productive, predictive model for

00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:45.140
continental R&D, it was going to be the first one put into production. So it was kind of

00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:48.619
important for the company, right?

00:05:48.619 --> 00:05:55.899
The developers really had to lay down some rules of engagement. We had to agree how it

00:05:55.899 --> 00:06:06.299
was we were going to get this off the ground. So yes, the guys ahead of me spoiled this.

00:06:06.299 --> 00:06:14.059
We had to agree on data exchange formats, right? First thing in the pipeline, we wanted

00:06:14.059 --> 00:06:20.420
to make sure that any one script could take outputs from any other script. So we agreed

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:28.779
to have our intermediate files would be parquet files. At the end of the pipeline or beginning

00:06:28.779 --> 00:06:35.339
of the pipeline, we needed to make sure that the rest of the company could access our results

00:06:35.459 --> 00:06:40.100
or that data from the rest of the company could come into the pipeline. So in that case,

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:46.220
we had post-press SQL databases.

00:06:46.220 --> 00:06:51.579
Another thing that happened in our daily development is that we agreed that we were going to do

00:06:51.579 --> 00:06:57.380
comfort zone coding. So no one developer needed to develop in something they weren't comfortable

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:01.779
in. Everybody, like, if I wanted to code in R, I could code in R. The other guys could

00:07:01.779 --> 00:07:10.779
code in Python. No problem. No hard feelings. But we did decide that for code review, we

00:07:10.779 --> 00:07:16.739
were going to do cross-language reviews because we wanted to enforce four-eyes principles.

00:07:16.739 --> 00:07:22.540
We also wanted to make sure that everybody had a basic understanding of what the new

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:27.500
contributions or refactoring to the code was going to be.

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:33.859
But when you review in a language that you're not very comfortable in, then, you know, you

00:07:33.859 --> 00:07:42.420
can't really make the code snazzier or super fancy, right? We had to adhere to core principles.

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:49.940
So like really the basics, talking about, you know, can I understand this code because

00:07:49.940 --> 00:07:55.500
the documentation is sufficient? So making sure people were documenting their code. Making

00:07:55.500 --> 00:08:01.820
sure they were naming things in a way that, you know, future us or future some other team

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:06.820
who is maintaining this will be able to understand what these objects or why they are called

00:08:06.820 --> 00:08:17.540
this or that. And, again, also trying to maintain, you know, function-based coding also.

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:25.980
So after we got that settled, so our day-to-day, then we also have to think about deployment.

00:08:25.980 --> 00:08:34.780
When you deploy something, you have to make sure that your code will run reliably many

00:08:34.780 --> 00:08:45.440
times. So every time it runs, it has to run well. So we really had to get beyond it works

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:50.760
on my machine. Thank you, Michael. I don't know where you are. So, yeah, we really needed

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:57.000
to get beyond this mentality. Because this code is not going to run on your machine,

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.280
right? It's going to be on the cloud. It's going to be on some, you know, platform, blah,

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:12.159
blah, blah. So how do you take care of making your code run reliably? You need to manage

00:09:12.159 --> 00:09:21.799
your environments, right? When I submitted this talk, so for R, we were using RM for

00:09:21.799 --> 00:09:27.719
package management. And when I submitted this talk for Python, we were using Poetry. And

00:09:27.719 --> 00:09:34.640
soon after, UV came out and I jumped on that bandwagon and it has been beautiful. And here

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:43.599
I disagree with Jeroen. Package management in Python is extremely easy with UV. And,

00:09:43.599 --> 00:09:53.400
yeah. Anyway. I'm going to also make a little aside here as to how things are different

00:09:53.400 --> 00:10:02.619
once UV came into the picture. So RM is very similar to Poetry, right? They both create

00:10:02.619 --> 00:10:11.059
lock files, which then Docker uses to create a Docker image. And those Docker images are

00:10:11.059 --> 00:10:19.739
those little containers in which we ship our R installation, our different packages, all

00:10:19.739 --> 00:10:27.580
of the dependencies, our code. Everything just lives inside of those little packages.

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:36.460
But when we move over to UV� wait a second. Okay. When we move over to UV, UV happens

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:44.419
to still use a base Docker image, but it installs all packages and dependencies on runtime extremely

00:10:44.419 --> 00:10:53.700
fast. And if anybody caught that� the talk about Rust and R this morning, it's because

00:10:53.700 --> 00:11:03.580
it's written in Rust. And, like, it completely blows my mind how fast this runs. What this

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:11.179
means for me on a daily basis is that I do not need to rebuild an image every time somebody

00:11:11.179 --> 00:11:15.460
adds something. Because every time you use a new package, I would need to rebuild the

00:11:15.460 --> 00:11:19.460
image because, remember, this is running somewhere else. It's not running on my machine. So I

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:25.780
need to rebuild the image. That can take really long. It's annoying. With UV, I do not need

00:11:25.780 --> 00:11:35.260
to do that anymore. I have heard that there is an RV in the works. And I am� I have

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:44.059
not had time to use it yet. It's actually already available. So I would love to be able

00:11:44.059 --> 00:11:47.340
to tell you that it works. I haven't used it yet.

00:11:47.340 --> 00:11:57.219
Okay. The next step in this process is containerization, which I've already spoiled a little bit. We

00:11:57.219 --> 00:12:04.020
need to use these Docker images to be able to contain our code in isolated environments.

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:10.619
And we created one for each language. So all of the Python code runs in a Docker image.

00:12:10.619 --> 00:12:18.859
Okay. Scratch that. We have� UV using this, right? So we have a Docker image with a base

00:12:18.859 --> 00:12:26.900
Python Docker image. And then we have a separate Docker image for our R code. And once this

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:35.900
all comes together, the orchestration is actually deployed on a language-agnostic MLOps platform.

00:12:35.900 --> 00:12:43.140
It doesn't care what you're running on it. All of the different steps in the pipeline

00:12:43.140 --> 00:12:53.219
are configured. How the different steps interact with each other, how� you know, what kind

00:12:53.219 --> 00:12:59.059
of resources you need, which outputs go where, which inputs get taken and where, that is

00:12:59.059 --> 00:13:10.219
all configured on this MLOps platform. So our final infrastructure looks something

00:13:10.219 --> 00:13:19.580
like this. This is a diagram of what the machine learning pipeline looks like. We have a lot

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:29.580
of AWS stuff in here. ValoHi is the MLOps platform that we use, which is based on Kubernetes.

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:34.539
We have the EC2 instances, which are the orange squares, and the S3 buckets, which are the

00:13:34.539 --> 00:13:43.739
green ones. And the different� the combination of Python and R is something like this. So,

00:13:43.739 --> 00:13:48.940
you know, some of these EC2s run Python code. Some of them run R code. And in the middle,

00:13:49.299 --> 00:13:56.619
we're just saving the outputs and grabbing them from the next node with whatever is coming

00:13:56.619 --> 00:14:04.460
next. The whole pipeline looks something like this. As I mentioned, those two databases

00:14:04.460 --> 00:14:14.340
on either side. And a Tableau dashboard at the end, which the tire developers are using.

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:27.739
So we were finally able to get to a deployed multilingual ML model that is nowadays used

00:14:27.739 --> 00:14:33.020
by over 100 developers a day. And we can give them overnight predictions instead of them

00:14:33.020 --> 00:14:42.679
having to wait about four months for a tire test. So how do you make R and Python play

00:14:42.719 --> 00:14:49.840
nice in production? Or at least how did we do it? We standardized the data exchange formats.

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:55.500
We took a pragmatic approach to coding and code review. And here I would say anything

00:14:55.500 --> 00:15:03.000
that works for your team is what works. Containerization for consistent environments. And language

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:11.039
agnostic orchestration. And yes, we can make R and Python work together and be productive.

00:15:11.039 --> 00:15:22.880
And we can leverage the benefits of both languages without having to compromise reliability.

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:28.880
And this is me. If you guys want to find me.

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:42.320
Excellent. We have a question or two. Why different Docker images for R and Python?

00:15:42.320 --> 00:15:43.320
Faster.

00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:46.520
That's a good answer.

00:15:46.520 --> 00:15:56.400
Yeah. I mean, there's really no need to load the R. I mean, I don't want to dis R. But

00:15:56.400 --> 00:16:03.900
the Docker image was about twice the size for R. It also had, like, we had everything

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:10.640
that happened in the ML pipeline in the R Docker. We could have probably cut that up

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:15.760
into ETL and maybe, you know, preprocessing and stuff like that. And then, like, the whole

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:21.440
tidyverse gets loaded in one. But just having to load the whole tidyverse and tidy models

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:28.200
and it gets pretty fat and heavy. So separate the Python from the R, and that makes both

00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:31.239
Dockers a little lighter and a little faster.

